  "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nWhen using Kotlin+Gradle (I haven't checked other configurations) and there is any compile error in the tests, you cannot start `quarkusDev` any more. This is very painful when you want to experiment with some changes that break the test compilation. Then your only chance is to either never restart quarkusDev (which you sometimes have to do) or to comment out all the breaking tests.\r\n\r\nThis is even the case when you disable continous testing with `quarkus.test.continuous-testing = disabled`.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nQuarkus Dev should start and if you have continous-testing active, it should tell you that some tests cannot be compiled. \n\n### Actual behavior\n\nQuarkus Dev does not start. It fails with \r\n\r\n```\r\n...\r\n> Task :compileTestKotlin FAILED\r\n5 actionable tasks: 2 executed, 3 up-to-date\r\n```\n\n### How to Reproduce?\n\n1. Download reproducer project: [2021-10-13_quarkus-dev-not-starting-due-to-test-error.zip](https://github.com/quarkusio/quarkus/files/7336518/2021-10-13_quarkus-dev-not-starting-due-to-test-error.zip)\r\n2. Run `./gradlew quarkusDev`\r\n3. It fails with an error that it cannot compile the tests.\n\n### Output of `uname -a` or `ver`\n\n_No response_\n\n### Output of `java -version`\n\n_No response_\n\n### GraalVM version (if different from Java)\n\n_No response_\n\n### Quarkus version or git rev\n\nQuarkus 2.3.0 but it occurs since continous testing was introduced.\n\n### Build tool (ie. output of `mvnw --version` or `gradlew --version`)\n\n_No response_\n\n### Additional information\n\n_No response_",
